  "prompt": "What are some great story books?",
  "response": "There are countless great story books across various genres and age groups. Here\u2019s a curated list of some timeless and beloved books for readers of all ages:\n\n---\n\n### **Classics**\n1. **Pride and Prejudice** by Jane Austen  \n2. **To Kill a Mockingbird** by Harper Lee  \n3. **1984** by George Orwell  \n4. **The Great Gatsby** by F. Scott Fitzgerald  \n5. **Moby-Dick** by Herman Melville  \n6. **Jane Eyre** by Charlotte Bront\u00eb  \n7. **Anna Karenina** by Leo Tolstoy  \n8. **Crime and Punishment** by Fyodor Dostoevsky  \n9. **The Catcher in the Rye** by J.D. Salinger  \n10. **Frankenstein** by Mary Shelley  \n\n---\n\n### **Fantasy and Science Fiction**\n1. **The Lord of the Rings** by J.R.R. Tolkien  \n2. **Harry Potter series** by J.K. Rowling  \n3. **The Chronicles of Narnia** by C.S. Lewis  \n4. **Dune** by Frank Herbert  \n5. **The Hitchhiker\u2019s Guide to the Galaxy** by Douglas Adams  \n6. **A Song of Ice and Fire series** by George R.R. Martin  \n7. **The Name of the Wind** by Patrick Rothfuss  \n8. **Ender\u2019s Game** by Orson Scott Card  \n9. **American Gods** by Neil Gaiman  \n10. **The Night Circus** by Erin Morgenstern  \n\n---\n\n### **Contemporary Fiction**\n1. **The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao** by Junot D\u00edaz  \n2. **The Kite Runner** by Khaled Hosseini  \n3. **A Little Life** by Hanya Yanagihara  \n4. **Where the Crawdads Sing** by Delia Owens  \n5. **The Goldfinch** by Donna Tartt  \n6. **Normal People** by Sally Rooney  \n7. **The Secret History** by Donna Tartt  \n8. **Pachinko** by Min Jin Lee  \n9. **Eleanor Oliphant Is Completely Fine** by Gail Honeyman  \n10. **The Vanishing Half** by Brit Bennett  \n\n---\n\n### **Young Adult**\n1. **The Hunger Games** by Suzanne Collins  \n2. **The Fault in Our Stars** by John Green  \n3. **The Book Thief** by Markus Zusak  \n4. **Percy Jackson and the Olympians series** by Rick Riordan  \n5. **Six of Crows** by Leigh Bardugo  \n6. **The Hate U Give** by Angie Thomas  \n7. **Wonder** by R.J. Palacio  \n8. **Scythe** by Neal Shusterman  \n9. **Children of Blood and Bone** by Tomi Adeyemi  \n10. **The Maze Runner** by James Dashner  \n\n---\n\n### **Children\u2019s Books**\n1. **Charlotte\u2019s Web** by E.B. White  \n2. **Matilda** by Roald Dahl  \n3. **The Phantom Tollbooth** by Norton Juster  \n4. **Harry Potter and the Sorcerer\u2019s Stone** by J.K. Rowling  \n5. **Alice\u2019s Adventures in Wonderland** by Lewis Carroll  \n6. **The Secret Garden** by Frances Hodgson Burnett  \n7. **Where the Wild Things Are** by Maurice Sendak  \n8. **A Wrinkle in Time** by Madeleine L\u2019Engle  \n9. **Peter Pan** by J.M. Barrie  \n10. **The Giving Tree** by Shel Silverstein  \n\n---\n\n### **Non-Fiction That Reads Like Fiction**\n1. **Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind** by Yuval Noah Harari  \n2. **Educated** by Tara Westover  \n3. **Into the Wild** by Jon Krakauer  \n4. **The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks** by Rebecca Skloot  \n5. **Just Kids** by Patti Smith  \n6. **Becoming** by Michelle Obama  \n7. **In Cold Blood** by Truman Capote  \n8. **The Glass Castle** by Jeannette Walls  \n9. **When Breath Becomes Air** by Paul Kalanithi  \n10. **Man\u2019s Search for Meaning** by Viktor E. Frankl  \n\n---\n\nThese books span a wide range of genres and styles, so there\u2019s something for everyone depending on your interests and mood! Let me know if you'd like recommendations tailored to a specific genre or theme.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
